TY  - JOUR
T1  - Dynamic Lot Size Models for Multi-Stage Assembly Systems
AU  - Crowston, Wallace B.
AU  - Wagner, Michael H.
Y1  - 1973/09/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.20.1.14
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.20.1.14
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 14
EP  - 21
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A multi-stage assembly system is a special case of Veinott's general multi-facility system in that each facility may have any number of predecessors but at most a single successor. This paper presents two algorithms for computing optimal lot sizes in such systems with known time-varying demand. The first is a dynamic programming algorithm for which solution time increases exponentially with the number of time periods, but only linearly with the number of stages, irrespective of assembly structure. The second is a branch and bound algorithm intended for cases where the number of time periods is large but the structure is close to serial. Computational results are given and extensions considered.
AB  - A multi-stage assembly system is a special case of Veinott's general multi-facility system in that each facility may have any number of predecessors but at most a single successor. This paper presents two algorithms for computing optimal lot sizes in such systems with known time-varying demand. The first is a dynamic programming algorithm for which solution time increases exponentially with the number of time periods, but only linearly with the number of stages, irrespective of assembly structure. The second is a branch and bound algorithm intended for cases where the number of time periods is large but the structure is close to serial. Computational results are given and extensions considered.
