TY  - JOUR
T1  - N-Job, One Machine Sequencing Problems Under Uncertainty
AU  - Blau, Roger A.
Y1  - 1973/09/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.20.1.101
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.20.1.101
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 101
EP  - 109
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - N jobs simultaneously arrive at a machine where they are to be processed. It is assumed that the processing times and due dates for the jobs are independent random variables whose distributions are known. The problem is to determine the optimal sequences of jobs, before processing begins, for various criteria of tardiness. It is shown that solutions are obtainable by ascertaining the optimal paths through a particular deterministic network. Furthermore, one may utilize a branch and bound technique to find these paths. For special classes of distributions, the solution procedure degenerates, whereby the optimal sequences may be determined by inspection.
AB  - N jobs simultaneously arrive at a machine where they are to be processed. It is assumed that the processing times and due dates for the jobs are independent random variables whose distributions are known. The problem is to determine the optimal sequences of jobs, before processing begins, for various criteria of tardiness. It is shown that solutions are obtainable by ascertaining the optimal paths through a particular deterministic network. Furthermore, one may utilize a branch and bound technique to find these paths. For special classes of distributions, the solution procedure degenerates, whereby the optimal sequences may be determined by inspection.
